     Only one of the 140 chemicals on EPA's regulated substance list is stored at the RWTF above the threshold.  This is the compressed liquid chlorine used in the disinfection process.  The maximum amount of chlorine contained onsite at any given time is 10,000 pounds.  This is stored in four one-ton cylinders.  The threshold quantity for chlorine is 2,500 pounds.



     Si has implemented safety precautions to prevent and mitigate a chlorine release.  These include maintenance, training, and inspection procedures, as well as an Emergency Action Plan, which has been coordinated with the local fire department.



     Chelford City MUD and Si are committed to:

?Preventing accidents;

?Training employees in correct response procedures in the event of an accident;

?Providing leadership to the community with respect to emergency preparedness;

?Addressing any citizen concerns by fully explaining potential hazards associated with facility operations and implementing all steps to prevent and mitigate accidents; and

?Being a good corporate citizen of Harris and Fort Bend Counties. 



     With these objectives in mind, this Risk Management Plan provides information about the Chelford City MUD and Si's management of the risk associated with the chlorine disinfection process, but more importantly stresses the commitment to ensuring a safe operation for employees, visitors, and community.
